#compdef adorn
# Documentation: source-direct extraction from upstream
# c-blake/bu adorn.nim (**Nim language**; uses
# **`cligen`** library — c-blake/cligen, by the same
# author as the bu package; corpus's first documented
# Nim cligen CLI, second Nim CLI library after R287
# stdlib `parseopt`):
#   adorn.nim line 2
#     (`import cligen, cligen/[sysUt, mfile, mslice,
#     osUt], std/parseutils` — Nim package import;
#     cligen is a third-party Nim library; bracket-
#     list import pulls multiple cligen submodules)
#   adorn.nim lines 10-11 (proc SIGNATURE defines the
#     CLI surface):
#     `proc adorn(colNums: seq[int], origin=1,
#                 O0=false, prefix=ess, suffix=ess,
#                 input="", rowDlm='\n', delim="w",
#                 output="")` =>
#       `colNums: seq[int]` ← positional varargs
#                              (seq[T] = vararg in
#                              cligen)
#       `origin=1`            ← --origin (int)
#       `O0=false`            ← --O0 (bool;
#                              CAPITALIZED preserved)
#       `prefix=ess`          ← --prefix (seq[string],
#                              `ess` = empty seq)
#       `suffix=ess`          ← --suffix (seq[string])
#       `input=""`            ← --input (string)
#       `rowDlm='\n'`         ← --rowDlm (Nim CHAR;
#                              single-quoted; \n is
#                              the newline escape)
#       `delim="w"`           ← --delim (string)
#       `output=""`           ← --output (string;
#                              gets short `-o` via
#                              line 54 short table)
#   adorn.nim lines 12-15 (`## ... \`input\`-
#     \`output\` filter to adorn fields by adding
#     \`prefix\` &| \`suffix\` to \`delim\`-ited
#     \`colNums\` ...` — Nim DOC-COMMENT `##` block
#     becomes the proc's docstring; cligen lifts the
#     docstring into the `--help` banner.  Nim's `##`
#     is the equivalent of Python's docstring +
#     Crystal's `# ` doc convention)
#   adorn.nim line 45 (`when isMainModule: dispatch
#     adorn, help={...}, short={"output":'o'}` —
#     CLIGEN `dispatch` MACRO at COMPILE TIME walks
#     the `adorn` proc signature, generates an argv
#     parser, calls `adorn(...)` with parsed values.
#     `help={...}` table provides per-param help
#     text; `short={...}` table overrides default
#     short-flag inference)
#   adorn.nim lines 46-54 (`help={"colNums": "...",
#     "origin": "...", "O0": "shorthand for
#     --origin=0", "prefix": "...", "suffix": "...",
#     "input": "...", "rowDlm": "...", "delim":
#     "...", "output": "..."}` — nine help-text
#     entries, one per proc param)
#   adorn.nim line 54 (`short={"output":'o'}` —
#     single short-flag override: `--output` gets
#     `-o`; all other shorts are AUTO-DERIVED by
#     cligen from the first letter of each long
#     name, with collisions resolved by
#     suppressing the conflicting short)
# Reference accessed: 2026-05-31 via gh api.
#
# adorn is a **column-aware text filter** — adds
# user-supplied PREFIXES and SUFFIXES to selected
# columns of a delimited input stream, preserving
# ambient text.  Part of c-blake/bu — a 77-star
# collection of "Basic But-For Utility" Nim
# programs (catz, cfold, cstats, dups, fage, etc.).
# Pivots from R300 hntop (V stdlib `flag`) into the
# **Nim cligen library cluster** — corpus's first
# documented Nim cligen CLI, second Nim CLI library
# after R287's stdlib `parseopt`.  **MAJOR
# MILESTONE**: expands the Nim slot in the cross-
# language CLI taxonomy from 1 to 2 variants —
# corpus now documents BOTH stdlib `parseopt` (R287
# nimpretty) and the de-facto standard third-party
# `cligen`.  Total library taxonomy: 40 variants.
#
# Critical extraction note: adorn uses **Nim
# `cligen` library** at adorn.nim:2 — c-blake/
# cligen is the **most popular Nim CLI library** by
# Charles Blake (also author of `bu`).  Distinct
# from Nim stdlib `parseopt` (R287 nimpretty) which
# is a TOKEN ITERATOR: caller drives a `getopt`
# loop and manually dispatches.  cligen is
# DECLARATIVE-VIA-MACRO: caller writes a NORMAL
# NIM PROC, then `dispatch procName` at compile
# time generates the argv parser + calls the proc.
# Documents the **proc-signature-as-CLI-spec via
# compile-time macro pattern** — sister to R296
# Julia Comonicon's function-signature-as-spec
# and R266 Python Click's decorator-on-function,
# but DIFFERENT from R287 Nim parseopt's iterator-
# driven loop.  cligen is to Nim what Click is to
# Python, Comonicon is to Julia, and Typer is to
# Python: SIGNATURE-AS-SPEC frameworks that
# eliminate spec/code duplication.  Extends cross-
# language CLI taxonomy to FORTY library variants
# — Nim slot now has TWO entries.  Corpus's
# **first documented Nim cligen CLI**.
#
# Critical extraction note: adorn uses **`dispatch
# PROC, help={...}` macro** at adorn.nim:45 — `when
# isMainModule: dispatch adorn, help={...},
# short={"output":'o'}` is cligen's COMPILE-TIME
# entry-point macro.  `dispatch PROC` (no quotes,
# PROC is a Nim symbol) tells cligen to walk
# `PROC`'s signature, then generate code that:
#   1. Parses argv into typed values matching the
#      proc params
#   2. Looks up per-param help text from the `help`
#      table
#   3. Looks up short-flag overrides from the
#      `short` table
#   4. Calls `PROC(...)` with parsed values
# Documents the **macro-walks-proc-signature
# pattern** — distinct from R296 Julia Comonicon
# `@main`-on-function (compile-time too but uses
# DOCSTRING for help) and R266 Python Click
# `@click.command()` (runtime decorator, NOT
# compile-time).  cligen's `dispatch` is a Nim
# template (a kind of macro) — it operates on
# the AST, not at runtime.  Corpus's **first
# documented macro-walks-proc-signature CLI**.
#
# Critical extraction note: adorn uses **`seq[T]`
# proc param → CLI positional varargs** at
# adorn.nim:10 — `colNums: seq[int]` (a Nim
# sequence-of-int) becomes the POSITIONAL varargs
# slot: `adorn 1 2 3 4` parses to `colNums = @[1,
# 2, 3, 4]`.  cligen has a CONVENTION: the
# `seq[T]` typed parameter receives all leftover
# positionals.  Multiple `seq[T]` params are
# disallowed (only one varargs slot per proc).
# Documents the **seq-T-as-varargs-positional
# pattern** — distinct from R296 Julia Comonicon
# (`args::Vector{String}` syntax) and R295 CL
# clingon (no per-spec positionals; goes through
# `cli:command-arguments`).  Plus `seq[T]`-typed
# proc params can appear as OPTIONS too (`--prefix
# A --prefix B` → `prefix = @["A", "B"]`) — same
# type, different position in the proc signature.
# Corpus's **first documented seq-T dual-mode
# (positional + option) CLI**.
#
# Critical extraction note: adorn uses **Nim `'\n'`
# CHARACTER literal for default** at adorn.nim:11
# — `rowDlm='\n'` declares a Nim `char` parameter
# with default `'\n'` (newline character; single-
# quoted with backslash escape).  Nim `char` is a
# UInt8 (single byte).  Documents the **Nim-char-
# literal CLI parameter pattern** — distinct from
# R298 Pony `'p'` (Pony char for short flag), R300
# V `\`n\`` (V backtick char for short flag).
# Nim's `'\n'` is the FIRST char-literal CLI
# PARAMETER (a value the user types, not a short
# flag designator) in the corpus.  When the user
# runs `adorn --rowDlm=A 1`, the `A` is parsed as
# a Nim `char`.  Convergent six character-literal
# cluster languages now: CL `#\X`, Erlang `$X`,
# Pony `'X'`, clingon (CL) `#\X`, V `\`X\``, Nim
# `'X'`.  Corpus's **sixth character-literal
# pattern (Nim variant)**.
#
# Critical extraction note: adorn uses **`##`
# doc-comment lifted into --help banner** at
# adorn.nim:12-15 — Nim's `##` is the DOC-COMMENT
# syntax (parsed by `nim doc`, hot-linked by IDE
# tooling).  cligen's `dispatch` macro reads the
# proc's `##` doc-comment and includes it as the
# `--help` banner at the top of the auto-generated
# help text.  Documents the **doc-comment-as-help-
# banner pattern** — sister to R296 Julia
# Comonicon's docstring-driven help (R296
# benchpkg).  TWO compile-time signature-walkers
# now: Julia Comonicon AND Nim cligen — both lift
# the documentation from the standard language
# documentation convention.  Distinct from R266
# Python Click `@click.command()` (NOT docstring-
# driven — uses `help=` kwarg or function
# `__doc__` lookup at runtime).  Convergent
# pattern: SIGNATURE-WALKING LIBRARIES tend to
# reuse the language's existing docstring
# convention for help text.
#
# Critical extraction note: adorn uses **`short=
# {"name":'c'}` table for short-flag override** at
# adorn.nim:54 — `short={"output":'o'}` tells
# cligen "`--output` should also have short `-o`".
# Without this table, cligen auto-derives shorts
# from first letter of each long name; collisions
# (e.g. both `--rowDlm` and `--rexp` would want
# `-r`) are resolved by SUPPRESSING the conflicting
# short.  The `short` table explicitly assigns or
# overrides.  Plus the value is a Nim `char`
# literal `'o'` — single-quoted as a single-byte
# character.  Documents the **explicit-short-
# override-table pattern** — distinct from R296
# Julia Comonicon (docstring-driven short
# discovery via `-X, --long <arg>` lines), R298
# Pony `OptionSpec.string("name", "...", 'p',
# "default")` (short is a positional arg of the
# option-spec call), and R295 CL clingon `:short-
# name #\A` (kwarg).  cligen's approach: shorts
# default to auto-derivation, but a `short` table
# lets you ENFORCE specific shorts.  Plus the use
# of a Nim TABLE LITERAL `{"output":'o'}` (curly-
# brace, key-value pair) makes it READABLE at the
# call site.  Corpus's **first documented short-
# override-table CLI pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: adorn uses **CAPITAL-
# CASE-PRESERVED Nim param `O0`** at adorn.nim:10
# — `O0=false` is a Nim proc parameter that
# becomes the CLI flag `--O0` LITERALLY (cligen
# does NOT lowercase or kebab-case it).  Per the
# inline help at line 48: `"O0": "shorthand for
# --origin=0"`.  Documents the **case-preserved
# CLI flag naming pattern** — distinct from R296
# Julia Comonicon's snake_case→kebab-case auto-
# conversion (`output_dir` → `--output-dir`).
# Nim's CamelCase and capitalized identifiers are
# PRESERVED VERBATIM by cligen — `O0` stays `O0`,
# `rowDlm` stays `rowDlm`.  This trades typing
# convenience (kebab-case is faster to type) for
# ROUND-TRIP IDENTITY (the flag name matches the
# proc-param name exactly).  Corpus's **first
# documented identifier-preserved CLI naming**.
#
# Critical extraction note: adorn uses **`when
# isMainModule:` guard** at adorn.nim:45 — Nim's
# `when isMainModule:` is a COMPILE-TIME
# CONDITIONAL that includes the block only when
# the module is the main entry point (analog to
# Python's `if __name__ == "__main__":`).  This
# means `adorn.nim` can be IMPORTED as a library
# (the `proc adorn` is exported) without
# triggering the CLI dispatch — only when COMPILED
# as a binary does the `dispatch adorn` macro
# generate the entry point.  Documents the **dual-
# library-and-binary pattern** — distinct from R296
# Julia Comonicon (separate `install()` function),
# R298 Pony `primitive CLI` (no dual usage), and
# R297 Prolog `main() :- ...` (separate predicate).
# Nim's `when isMainModule:` is COMPILE-TIME — the
# library-vs-binary decision is made before the
# binary is built.  Corpus's **first documented
# dual-library-and-binary CLI pattern**.
#
# Hunt-skip notes: skipped `_nimpretty` (R287
# nimpretty stdlib parseopt is the FIRST Nim CLI
# in corpus; this round is the SECOND Nim slot).
# Probed `nimterop/nimterop loaf.nim` (cligen
# `dispatchMulti` with single `find` subcommand —
# would be `loaf find ...` but smaller surface
# than adorn; deferred), `c-blake/cligen util/
# complgen.nim` (cligen's own completion generator
# — meta-tool; complex), `godot-nim/gdext-nim
# coronation/src/coronation.nim` (Godot C++/Nim
# binding generator), `genotrance/feud feud.nim`
# (game/scripting tool), `pysan3/minorg minorg.nim`
# (small adoption), `jhbadger/nimbioseq examples/
# checkFastq.nim` (bioinformatics example),
# `jakobfriedl/conquest src/client/main.nim`
# (CTF tool), various nibSV/scinim/yourutils
# probes.  Chose adorn: AUTHORED BY CLIGEN
# AUTHOR (Charles Blake), 9-param proc with
# canonical cligen pattern surface (positional
# varargs via seq[int], multiple typed defaults,
# explicit `short={}` override, `help={}` table),
# real binary published in c-blake/bu nimble
# package (bu.nimble bin=@[..., "adorn", ...]),
# stable 0.18.13 version.

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line

# 9 params decoded source-direct from adorn proc
# signature at adorn.nim:10-11 + help/short tables
# at adorn.nim:45-54.  Note: cligen auto-derives
# most short flags from first letter; explicit
# overrides only for --output (-o) per line 54.
_arguments -s -S \
  '*--prefix=[strings to prepend to listed columns (repeatable)]:prefix:' \
  '*--suffix=[strings to append to listed columns (repeatable)]:suffix:' \
  '--origin=[origin for colNums; 0 => signed indexing (default: 1)]:n:' \
  '--O0[shorthand for --origin=0]' \
  '--input=[path to mmap|read as input ("" => stdin)]:input file:_files' \
  '--rowDlm=[input row delimiter character (default: newline)]:char:' \
  '--delim=[input field delimiter chars (len>0=>fold; w=white) (default: w)]:delimiter:' \
  '(-o --output)'{-o,--output}'=[path to write output file ("" => stdout)]:output file:_files' \
  '--help[show adorn help]' \
  '*:column numbers (origin-origin column numbers):'
